featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
Nag Ghat - This is the place Paithan village on the bank of Godavari in Marathwada where Sri Sant Dnyaneshwar at the age of 12 called Redya Mukhi Veda that a man was killing his Redya mercilessly by the river bank. Dnyaneshwar was not allowed to see it. They immediately requested the owner to stop the beating. Then one Pandil said that for his question we are talking about the Vedas but this hermit's son is more worried about Redya.
Dnyaneshwar immediately replied. It is said in the Vedas that all living beings are sacred, that Brahman (Parabrahman / Divine Essence) resides in all living beings. So Redya's life is not as important as our life?
On this, those pundits started making fun of him. Big came to teach us Vedas. According to you, if that Reda and the pundits we studied the Vedas are the same, can't that Reda also recite the Vedas like us?
Dnyaneshwar said why not. He went near Redya and placed his hand on Redya's head. and miracles. He started calling Reda as Richa of Vedas. So this is the holy ghat where this incident happened

This location - popularly known as Naag Ghat is a historical place.
Dating back to the time when Sant Dnyaneshwar visited Paithan.

One can hire an autorickshaw. The driver also plays the role of a guide.

The local people are peace-loving, cooperative and helpful. (Provided you are respectful)

Thank you.
